  "prompt": "Are prunes more likely to make you poop than other kinds of dried fruit? If not, how did they get that association?",
  "response": "Prunes do have a stronger association with promoting bowel movements compared to other dried fruits, and this reputation is largely due to their specific nutritional composition. Here\u2019s why:\n\n1. **High Sorbitol Content**: Prunes (dried plums) are particularly rich in sorbitol, a sugar alcohol that acts as a natural laxative. Sorbitol is not fully absorbed in the intestines, so it draws water into the gut, softening stool and stimulating bowel movements.\n\n2. **Dietary Fiber**: Prunes also contain a significant amount of dietary fiber, both soluble and insoluble. Fiber adds bulk to stool and helps regulate digestion. While other dried fruits (like apricots, figs, and raisins) also contain fiber, prunes have a higher fiber-to-calorie ratio.\n\n3. **Phenolic Compounds**: Prunes contain phenolic compounds that may stimulate the muscles in the digestive tract, further aiding in bowel movements.\n\n### Why the Association?\nThe association between prunes and bowel regularity dates back centuries. They have long been used in traditional medicine as a remedy for constipation, and their effectiveness has been supported by modern research. Studies have shown that prunes are more effective than many other laxatives for treating mild to moderate constipation.\n\nWhile other dried fruits like figs, apricots, and dates can also help with digestion due to their fiber content, they don\u2019t contain as much sorbitol or have the same laxative effect as prunes. This is why prunes are more strongly associated with promoting bowel movements.\n\n### In Summary\nPrunes are indeed more likely to make you poop than other dried fruits due to their unique combination of sorbitol, fiber, and phenolic compounds. Their long-standing reputation as a natural laxative is well-deserved and backed by science.",
